[unused] St. Petersburg Times February 20 , 2002 Pg. 1
[unused] 72 Hours At Camp X- Ray
[unused] As the detention camp reaches capacity , reporters are invited to watch the interplay between detainees , guards and doctors .
[unused] By Paul De La Garza
[unused] GUANTANAMO BAY NAVAL BASE , Cuba -
[unused] It begins as a shiny speck in the southeast skies of the lone landing strip here at Gitmo , the oldest U.S. base overseas .
[unused] Within minutes the lumbering , gray C-141B Starlifter flies low over the tarmac and over a patch of palm trees , as if part of an annual air show .
[unused] On a hot and windy afternoon , the deep blue waters of the Caribbean serve as the postcard backdrop .
[unused] When the cargo jet finally lands , approaching the landing strip from the west , the noise is deafening .
[unused] Almost immediately a crack security force of mostly baby - faced Marines surrounds the plane .
[unused] They wear black baseball leg guards and bulletproof vests and carry M-16 rifles .
[unused] Meanwhile , Humvees mounted with .50 - caliber machine guns and 40 mm grenade launchers take their positions .
[unused] A Navy helicopter whirls overhead .
[unused] Once the aircraft is secured , the freak show begins , a sort of " Hannibal the Cannibal " production .
[unused] Down the back ramp of the mammoth aircraft , the guards slowly unload the latest detainees from the war in Afghanistan , 34 altogether .
[unused] Wearing bright orange wool knit caps , blacked - out goggles , earmuffs , white surgical masks , bright orange jumpsuits , denim jackets , beige mittens ( taped around the wrists ) , handcuffs and ankle shackles , the detainees do n't look natural .
[unused] They look like giant bright orange flies .
[unused] After a 25 - hour flight of mostly sitting , the prisoners hobble along as the Marines , who look twice as big , walk them out and frisk them .
[unused] One soldier handles a captive like a mannequin - moving him back , forward , and to the side - before lifting him straight off his feet and onto one of two waiting buses .
[unused] " Walk !
[unused] Walk ! " the guards shout .
[unused] " Shut up !
[unused] Head down ! "
[unused] " Man , they must be so scared , " says a TV camerawoman watching with an international media pool from about 400 yards away .
[unused] " It must be freaky , " chimes in her colleague .
[unused] The prisoners are here because the military considers them " hard- core " terrorists - willing to escape , to kill themselves and others .
[unused] But now they do pretty much as directed .
[unused] They walk , they shut up , they lower their heads .
[unused] They board buses that will take them to a ferry that will take them across Guantanamo Bay to a detention facility known as Camp X - Ray .
[unused] A sign near the ferry slip conveys some of the strange vibe of Guantanamo , a 45 - square mile naval base in which the detention camp comprises some 3 acres .
[unused] The sign touts the area 's wildlife - the brown pelican , the Antillean manatee , the bottlenose dolphin , the hawksbill turtle .
[unused] " Watching wildlife can be a lot of fun , " says the sign .
[unused] " A pair of binoculars is helpful . "
[unused] Last Wednesday , the 10th flight from Kandahar to the southeastern tip of Cuba arrived , bringing the total number of detainees at Camp X -Ray to 288 .
[unused] A day later , another 12 came , effectively filling the camp to capacity .
[unused] Base officials allowed reporters to record audio and report the landings live via cell phone for the first time since the flights began arriving Jan. 11 .
[unused] They refused to allow cameras .
[unused] The last time the Pentagon released pictures of the detainees - on their knees , wearing the goggles , and surrounded by guards - the images created an international uproar .
[unused] Rights groups cried inhumane treatment .
[unused] Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld denied the allegations , insisting that the detainees have it better here than in Afghanistan .
[unused] And he did what he routinely does when questioned about the way the United States is prosecuting the war on terrorism :
[unused] He reminded critics of Sept. 11 .
[unused] When the detainees arrive at Camp X - Ray , they are told they 're in Cuba and then undergo a 45 - minute intake process , which , like the airstrip landing , is monitored by the Red Cross .
[unused] The routine includes a delousing , or chemical washdown , and a physical .
[unused] The detainees also get fingerprinted and photographed .
[unused] They get a toothbrush , mint-flavored toothpaste , a bottle of " Lively Salon " antidandruff shampoo , soap , flip flops , a foam sleeping mat , two buckets , a washcloth , a canteen , a prayer cap , two blankets , a sheet , a Koran and two towels , one for praying .
[unused] And , strangely , they get to write home .
[unused] It 's not that the U.S. military has a soft spot for the mothers of the Taliban or al - Qaida .
[unused] Instead , base officials try to glean the prisoners ' real names from the letters , as many tend to give multiple aliases during interrogations .
[unused] When they 're done , they 're assigned to the cells in which they will begin their new lives .
[unused] These are 8 - feet-square , with chain - link sides and tin roofs .
[unused] The Halogen lights stay on all night .
[unused] The next day starts with prayer call about 5 a.m .
[unused] A sign on a pole at the edge of the camp points the direction to Mecca .
[unused] The prisoners come from 31 countries , including Saudi Arabia , Yemen , Pakistan , Algeria , England , Egypt , Australia , France , Russia , Belgium and Sweden .
[unused] Base officials say there are Christian prisoners as well as Muslims .
[unused] After prayer , the detainees ' day goes like this : breakfast , a shower ( every other day ) , sick call , noon prayer , lunch , recreation ( 15 minutes a couple of times a week ) , mail call , sunset prayer , dinner , evening prayer and bedtime around 9 p.m .
[unused] Each meal the detainees get is considered halal , or religiously appropriate for Muslims .
[unused] A typical breakfast includes oatmeal , an orange , fresh bread and a bottle of water .
[unused] For lunch , it 's pasta or vegetable stew , dry cereal including Froot Loops , a box of raisins , two granola bars , a bag of chips , and bag of peanuts and water .
[unused] For dinner they get white rice , red beans , a banana and water .
[unused] U.S. Army Capt . Sean Campion , one of the camp guards , characterizes life at Camp X -Ray as " utter boredom . "
[unused] " If you do your job right , " says Campion , 32 , of Kansas City , Mo. , " nothing is scheduled to happen . "
[unused] The guards mostly communicate with the prisoners via simple English commands and hand signals .
[unused] " We 're not holding any lengthy debates with them or anything , " Campion says .
[unused] Marine Corps Lt. Abuhena Mohammad Saiful -Islam , 39 , speaks more with the detainees than almost anybody at the camp .
[unused] As the Muslim chaplain , he ministers at the facility up to five hours every day .
[unused] He says that with the start of the Muslim month of pilgrimage , during which the faithful journey to the holy city of Mecca , he detects more anxiety in the camp .
[unused] Base officials are considering a special meal for March 10 .
[unused] " The role of chaplain is unique , " Saiful - Islam says .
[unused] " We do n't go with a preconceived idea that the person is so and so .
[unused] As a chaplain we approach them as a human being .
[unused] " We do n't hate the sinner , " he says , " but we hate the sin . "
[unused] Somebody asks Saiful -Islam if the relationship between the detainees and God has changed since their capture .
[unused] " They have n't said that God has abandoned them , because they know , " he says .
[unused] " That 's the hope that they have , that God is their only hope .
[unused] " They do ask me what 's going to happen .
[unused] At this moment , I do n't have an answer . "
[unused] Concertina wire and nine guard towers surround Camp X - Ray .
[unused] The American flag is everywhere - painted on the guard towers , flying high in front of the facility .
[unused] Unlike other parts of the base , the camp does not have a pretty setting .
[unused] Turkey vultures hover over thick brush and scraggly hills .
[unused] It is day two at X - Ray for the 34 newly arrived from Kandahar .
[unused] A German shepherd and his handler patrol the camp 's perimeter .
[unused] Bright orange figures sit in their cells , some of them praying .
[unused] One or two prisoners run for exercise in a fenced area , wearing handcuffs but no ankle shackles .
[unused] Every so often a prisoner is led to one of five interrogation rooms , freshly built wood buildings with air conditioners and no windows .
[unused] Three guards accompany him - one on either side and one behind .
[unused] One of the guards puts a hand behind the head of the detainee , forcing him to look down .
[unused] This is done to " provide positive control , " says U.S. Army Col .
[unused] Terry Carrico , in effect the prison warden .
[unused] " It means he ca n't look ahead .
[unused] He ca n't make a plan .
[unused] They do n't know where they 're going .
[unused] That 's a technique across correctional facilities in the United States . "
[unused] Except for an occasional spitting incident or threat , officials say , the prisoners are docile .
[unused] Base officials suspect that the people already in custody pass the word along to the new arrivals that they will be treated okay .
[unused] " In the beginning , they were very unsure , " says Carrico .
[unused] " They did n't know if we were going to take care of them , hurt them or kill them . "
[unused] Some guards do n't want to talk about their views of the prisoners .
[unused] But U.S. Army Capt. Darrell Sides , 30 , of Fort Benning , Ga. , makes no bones about considering them terrorists .
[unused] " We were all watching television Sept. 11 , " he says .
[unused] " The security here I would consider tighter than death row in a prison in the United States . "
[unused] The morning run to Fleet Hospital 20 takes place as scheduled .
[unused] This is for prisoners needing medical attention , as a fair number do .
[unused] Some are underweight , others are missing toes , fingers and limbs .
[unused] The hospital is several miles from Camp X-Ray , off Recreation Road .
[unused] Along the way , if allowed , the detainees would get to see a bit of Americana , a portrait built over the past century .
[unused] U.S. forces seized Guantanamo Bay during the Spanish-American War .
[unused] In 1903 , the U.S. government signed a lease with the Republic of Cuba .
[unused] That contract , extended indefinitely in 1934 , can be broken only by mutual agreement .
[unused] The growth of the base has left Camp X - Ray surprisingly close to a suburban -style military community of beige , green and yellow houses in subdivisions with names like Caribbean Circle and West Iguana .
[unused] Two boys in white karate outfits run down palm-lined Sherman Avenue .
[unused] Another child , no more than 3 or 4 , plays on a gym set , with a young woman keeping a watchful eye .
[unused] Also up the road is the W.S. Sampson Elementary School , replete with yellow school buses , the Morale Welfare and Recreation Cooper Field with baseball and soccer fields , and the base 's outdoor movie house , which is playing the movie , The Majestic .
[unused] The 20 - bed hospital is a high-tech , air-conditioned white tent which looks like a futuristic movie set , with low ceilings , fluorescent lighting , and padded white walls , floors and ceilings .
[unused] The staff calls it a " temper tent . "
[unused] On this morning , U.S. Navy hospital corpsman Shuron Jerome , 19 , of Houston is poring over a box of Valentines sent to Guantanamo by schoolchildren in Pennsylvania .
[unused] " Wish you could be with your family , " one child has written .
[unused] Jerome says the hospital feels no different than a hospital in the states , save for the high security and the various languages the detainees speak , including French , Russian , Urdu and Arabic .
[unused] Most understand a little English , she says .
[unused] While she sees the detainees as patients , she allows that they 're not " regular patients . "
[unused] She often finds herself thinking , " Oh , my God , they could be related to this or related to that .
[unused] But I still try to treat them as a patient . "
[unused] Fleet Hospital 20 has nine patients today .
[unused] The bulk of the work includes blast and gunshot wounds from the war in Afghanistan .
[unused] Just the other day , however , a surgeon took out the eye of a patient who had suffered a sports injury when he was younger .
[unused] The pressure on the eye had become unbearable .
[unused] The story got international play because it seemed to underscore the fact that tensions between the Americans and the detainees were easing .
